Here's the complete migration with key pitfalls explained:

## ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) Migration

```csharp
// ReportController.cs
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    private readonly ILogger<ReportController> _logger;

    public ReportController(ILogger<ReportController> logger)
    {
        _logger = logger;
    }

    // File export — replaces Response.Write/End pattern
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ExportReport()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();
        var bytes = System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data);
        return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
    }

    // Redirect — replaces Response.Redirect(url, endResponse: true)
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAndRedirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return RedirectToAction("Index", "Login"); // or Redirect("/login")
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // No more ThreadAbortException — remove that catch entirely
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            _logger.LogError(ex, "Request processing failed");
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

### 1. `Response.End()` / `Response.Redirect(url, true)` → gone
ASP.NET Framework used `Thread.Abort()` internally to halt execution. **ASP.NET Core has no equivalent** — `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET Core+. Return `IActionResult` instead of writing to `Response` directly.

### 2. Remove all `ThreadAbortException` catches
```csharp
// ❌ WRONG — this exception no longer exists in normal flow
catch (ThreadAbortException) { }

// ✅ Just remove it — redirects are now return values, not exceptions
```

### 3. `Response.Write()` → return action results
```csharp
// ❌ Old pattern — writes directly to the response stream
Response.Clear();
Response.ContentType = "text/csv";
Response.AddHeader("Content-Disposition", "...");
Response.Write(data);
Response.End();

// ✅ New pattern — framework handles headers/content
return File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
```

### 4. `Response.Redirect()` no longer terminates execution
```csharp
// ❌ Dangerous — code CONTINUES executing after this in Core
Response.Redirect("/login");
DoSomethingElse(); // THIS WILL RUN

// ✅ Return the redirect — nothing runs after return
return Redirect("/login");
```

### 5. Authentication should use middleware
```csharp
// In Program.cs — replaces manual IsAuthenticated checks
builder.Services.AddAuthentication(/* ... */);
app.UseAuthentication();
app.UseAuthorization();

// On the action or controller:
[Authorize]
[HttpPost]
public IActionResult ProcessAndRedirect()
{
    // Unauthenticated users never reach here — redirected automatically
    ProcessRequest();
    return Redirect("/success");
}
```

### 6. `Response.AddHeader()` → `Response.Headers.Append()`
If you must set headers manually (rare with action results):
```csharp
// ❌ Old
Response.AddHeader("X-Custom", "value");

// ✅ New
Response.Headers.Append("X-Custom", "value");
```

## Summary of Patterns

| ASP.NET Framework | ASP.NET Core |
|---|---|
| `Response.Write()` + `Response.End()` | `return Content()` / `return File()` |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `return Redirect(url)` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | **Delete it** |
| `Response.Clear()` | Not needed — response isn't started yet |
| `Response.AddHeader()` | `Response.Headers.Append()` |
| Manual `IsAuthenticated` checks | `[Authorize]` attribute |

The core mental model shift: **ASP.NET Framework used side effects** (write to response, abort thread). **ASP.NET Core uses return values** (return an `IActionResult` and the framework writes the response).
